{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2boccioni_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604732/1946042001/0151.xml":{"full_text":"W gening fsfaV\nWith Sunday Moraine Edition.\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor.\nWAS HI NGTO N, d7~cT\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company.\nMain Office: 11th St and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNev, York Office: 1 10 East 42d St.\nChicago Office: 485 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area.\nEffective October 1. 1044.\nRecular Edition. 4 Sundays. 5 Sundays.\nEvening and Sunday. 90c per tno SI 00 per mo.\nThe Evening Star- tiOc per month.\nThe Sunday Star loc Per copy.\nNitht rEinai Edition. 4 Sundays. 5 Sundays.\nNieht FirfU and Sunday $1 immo SI.10 mo.\nNight Pinal Star_ 75c Per month.\nKates by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAn>where in United States.\n1 month t> months. 1 year.\nEvening and Sunday. Si.on do jj-jtiO\nThe Evening Star_ .75 4 00 8 00\nThe 8unday Star_ 50 2.50 5.00\nTelephone National 5000.\nEntered at the Post Office. Washington, D. C.,\naa second-class mail matter.\nMember of the Associated Press.\n..The Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nthe use for republication of all news dispatches\ncredited to it or not otherwise credited in this\nPaper and also the. local news published herein.\nA.l rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein aiso are reserved\nA\u20146 SAT U11 DA Y~ A pri 1JM), 1946\nConstructive Report\nThere have been many investiga\ntions of the District Jail over a long\nperiod of years, but none has pro\nduced a report more constructive, on\nthe whole, than that submitted to\nthe House District Committee by the\nHebert Subcommittee. The subcom\nmittee placed its finger on a fun\ndamental weakness of the present\nadministration of the jail when it\ncriticized the divided responsibility\nof the existing setup\u2014with the Dis\ntrict Commissioners responsible for\nseeking appropriations and the\nBoard of Public Welfare responsible\nfor operation of local penal institu\ntions. It was almost inevitable that\nsuch a division of authority should\nresult in conflict and controversy,\nwith resultant breakdowns in effi\nciency and morale at the jail. The\nsubcommittee proposes to end this\nsplit jurisdiction by establishing,\nunder the Commissioners, a Depart\nment of Corrections which would\nhave complete responsibility for ad\nministering the jail and other local\npenal establishments. Heading this\ndepartment, the subcommittee says,\nshould be a competent penologist,\npreferably obtained through co-op\neration of the Federal Bureau of\nPrisons.\nBecause the immediate situation\nat the jail is urgent, the subcommit\ntee recommends that this new de\npartment be created at once\u2014by\njoint agreement between the Com\nmissioners and the Board of Public\nWelfare. This admittedly would be\nan interim voluntary arrangement,\npending proposed legalization of the\nplan by statute. The subcommittee\npaid proper tribute to the public\nspiritedness of the Welfare Board,\nwhose members, serving without pay,\nhave tried valiantly but vainly to\nmake the present hydra-headed sys\ntem work. As the subcommittee\npoints out, the board has been seri\nously handicapped by its general\nunfamiliarity with technical details\nof prison administration. By volun\ntarily agreeing to transfer its admin\nistrative authority over the jail to a\nnew department headed by a prison\nexpert, the board would make a\npraiseworthy contribution to solu\ntion of the jail problem.\nIt is interesting to note, that a\nnumber of the reforms recommended\nby the subcommittee already had\nbeen advocated by the suspended\ngeneral superintendent, Mr. Gill,\nwhose dismissal the subcommittee\nurges. He is on record as favoring a\nseparate department of corrections,\nstrengthening of safeguards against\nescape and adoption of some other\nmeasures in the subcommittee\u2019s pro\ngram. Since the question of Mr.\nGills fitness to continue as penal\nsuperintendent is being considered\nbv a special board which has held\nlengthy hearings on the subject, it\nis assumed that the final decision as\nio Mr. Gill\u2019s future will await the\nverdict of that board.\nThe long-view approach to the jail\nproblem suggested by the subcom\nmittee would involve creation of a\nspecial committee composed of rep\nresentatives of the House District\nCommittee, the District Court, the\nDepartment rrf Justice, the Commis\nsioners and the citizens of Washing\nton. This group would be charged\nwith preparing a comprehensive,\nup-to-date program of penal admin\nistration for the District, including\nrecommendations for legislation con\nsidered necessary to remedy existing\ndefects. It is to be hoped that such\na committee will be named in the\nnear future and that it will tackle its\ndifficult assignment at the earliest\npracticable moment.\nDr. Dandy\nDead of heart disease at sixty.\nWalter Edward Dandy has left a\nname which almost certainly will\nendure for generations. He was one\nof the great creative pioneers in the\ndifficult field of neurological surgery\nand as such will be remembered not\nonly by his professional followers\nbut by the public at large. The story\nof his career already is a popular\nlegend. It will be part of the history\nof modern American medicine as\nlong as the healing art itself survives.\nDr. Dandy\u2019s life, however, was\nnothing extraordinary as he person\nally saw it. He disclaimed romantic\ninterpretations of his work. Born\nat Sedalia, Missouri, in 1886, he at\ntended the university of his native\nState from 1907 until he transferred\nto JolriS Hopkins in 1910. The\nfamous surgical mentor, Dr. William\nStewart Halsted, persuaded him to\nspecialize in the study of the brain\nand the nervous system. When he\nhad made that decision, he abided\nby it faithfully. During three long\nand inordinately busy decades, he\ncourageously experimented, bravely\noperated, wrote and taught in Balti\nmore. His achievement, summarized\nin his gwn language, is told in fifty\nsix words in current biographical\ndictionaries.\nExplained in less rigidly technical\nterms, Dr. Dandy\u2019s services to suffer\ning humanity were these: He dis\ncovered new ways for locating and\nphotographing brain tumors and\nnew techniques for removing those\nmalignant growths when found; he\ntraced low backaches and sciaticas\nto ruptured spinal disks and per\nfected surgical procedures for their\ncare; he demonstrated his methods\nto other, younger physicians who will\ncarry on his work.\nObviously, Dr. Dandy best can be j\neulogized by those who knew him\niutimately. The lay community\nnonetheless has an obligation to\nput its appreciation of him on\nrecord. He was above all else an\nAmerican citizen, sharing as the\ngenerality of his contemporaries did\nin the development of the Nation.\nBrusque in manner often, sharp of\ntongue on occasion, he was armored\nthus against disturbing sentimental\nity. Yet he was capable of vast\nspontaneous generosity, steady and\npatient kindness. There was too\nmuch sorrow in the world for him to\nbe completely happy even in the\ntriumphs which he won. Content\nment never came to him. Not long\nbefore the end, he said to a colleague\nthat he wished he could do more.\nSuch an attitude was characteristic\nof him. It is good to know that his\ncontribution to science, to increased\nknowledge of how to treat pain, will\nj continue indefinitely.\nWe Recognize Tito\nThe full diplomatic recognition ex\ntended by our Government to the i\nYugoslav regime headed by Marshal\nTito marks the end of a somewhat\nuncertain course of American policy\ntowards that Balkan country.\nIt begins with the gradual with\ndrawal, first of assistance and later\nof diplomatic intercourse by Wash\nington from the government of King\nPeter in favor of the rival Yugoslav\nregime of Tito. In this, we tended to\nfollow' the line of British diplomacy, I\nw'hich, in turn was motivated by\n\u201chigher\u201d considerations of Anglo\nRussian policy.\nYugoslavia, of course, formed an 1\nexception to its Balkan neighbors in\nthat it resisted the Axis and thus fell\nI into another category than Austria,\nj Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria, all\nI of whom had formed part of the Axis\nbloc. Still, it was apparently under\nstood at the Yalta and Potsdam Con\nferences that the formula there\nevolved should apply to Yugoslavia;\nnamely, that the \u201cBig Three\u201d should\nassist in the re-establishment of its\npolitical life, attained by the estab-\nlishment of a postwar government\nrepresenting all parties not tarred by\n\u201ccollaborationism\u201d with the Axis and\nchosen through free elections.\nIt soon became obvious that the\nTito regime was not living up to the\nformula. The \u201cagreement\u201d which\nTito made to accept representatives\nof other parties ended in their res\nignation because of the intolerable\nsituation wherein they found them\nselves. This was followed last No\nvember by \u201celections\u201d held under\nsuch conditions that they were far\ncical in character. Accordingly, last\nDecember, our State Department\nsent the Tito regime a note making j\nclear our disapproval and saying\nthat it wished to be understood that\n\u201cestablishment of diplomatic rela\ntions with the present regime in\nYugoslavia should not be interpreted\nas implying approval of the policies j\nof the regime or its failure to imple\nment the guarantees ^f personal\nfreedom promised its people.\u201d\nAmerican disapproval of its acts\nhad no effect upon the Tito regime,\nstrongly backed as it was by Moscow.\nWhat the State Department has now\ndone is to recognize the Tito regime\nnotwithstanding, on receipt of for\nmal assurance that the regime was\nprepared to observe existing treaties\nand agreements betwen the two\ncountries, these being routine mat\nters such as commerce, naturaliza\ntion, extradition and the like.\nSince Yugoslavia stood on a dif\nferent wartime sta'tus from the Axis\nsatellite countries, its formal rec\nognition need not necessarily form\nj a precedent for Washington\u2019s action\ntoward them. On the other hand, it\nmay betoken a desire to regularize J\nour diplomatic relations with a part\nof the world which is clearly in the\nRussian orbit and about which we\nhave thus far been able to do very\nlittle to the contrary.\nDr. Evans' Report\nIf the Library of Congress were\nmerely the largest bibliographic\nestablishment on earth, it would be\na comparatively unimportant insti\ntution. Only when it is remembered\nthat it is a great working organiza-\ntion, engaged in a multiplicity of j\ndifferent services to the Nation and I\nto the world beyond, is its authentic\ni significance realized. Dr. Luther H.\nEvans, in his first annual report as\nj librarian in charge, deals with the\nenterprises over which he presides\nin the light of the distinction thus\nexpressed. He tells of the heavy\ndemands which were made upon the j\nfacilities of the Library by the Gov\nernment and the armed forces during\nthe Second World War, and he\nclaims for his staff, as he properly\nshould, a share of the credit for\nthe victory finally achieved.\nBut the task of the past, as Dr.\nEvans views it, was a small affair\ncompared with the job which lies\nahead. The United States, he in\nsists, must possess \u2018\u2018the printed, the\npictorial, the cartographic and the\nother material which will be needed\u201d\nin the years to come. Further, this\naccumulation must be comprehended\nand understood in pragmatic terms.\nTo study the data now available and\nyet to be acquired, the Librarian\ncalls for \u2018\u2018men and women with\ntrained, talented and resourceful\nminds\u201d\u2014people competent to ap\npraise the values gathered and to\nprocess them into channels of public\nadvantage.\nApplicants for help of one variety\nor another, Dr. Evans explains, are\ncoming to the Library in ever\nincreasing throngs. The number of\nreaders rose more than a hundred\nthousand in 1945. Over a million\nand a half different \u201cpieces\u201d\u2014books,\npamphlets, manuscripts, maps, pho\ntographs, etc.\u2014were brought from\nshelves and cabinets to be used by\ncitizens of every class and by many\nvisitors from other lands, including\nsome whose own libraries had been\ndestroyed in $he struggle with the\nAxis enemies. More than a thousand\ncongressional inquiries a month\nwere \u201chandled\u201d by the Legislative\nReference Service alone, and it\nshould be mentioned in this connec\ntion that the \u201chandling\u201d of such\nquestions cannot be and is not\ncasual.\nThe same observation applies to\nrequests for aid from co-operating\nlibraries overseas. Dr. Evans asserts\nfor his organization that it strives\nfor \u201cthe removal of false partitions\nbetween nation and nation.\u201d The goal\nset for the Library, then, is universal\nin its application. It is in the largest\nbibliographic establishment on earth\nas a force working in the widest\nconceivable field for the correction\nof ignorance and the terrible fruits\nof ignorance that the Librarian\nputs his faith. He sees the Library\nas a power for peace and for life\nworth living. Perhaps the most\nmeaningful words in the entirety\nof his report are these: \u201cBy the\ncommon efforts of mankind, com\nmonly applied, knowledge as con\ntained in the records man has made,\nnow hidden behind the confusion of\nhis symbols, may be recovered,\nrecorded and mastered for the\nenlightenment and welfare of the\nhuman family.\u201d\nEvery road ^traditionally leads to\nRome, but by the same logic every\nroad also leads to at least one other\nplace\u2014which is as it should be, since\notherwise the Hub of the Universe\nwould be crowded intolerably.\nPink rattlesnakes have been found\non the floor of the Grand Canyon.\nCould it be possible that some of the\nthousands of empty bottles thrown\ninto the Canyon every year were not\nempty after all?\nFishermen ought to be trusted, if\nIzaak Walton be right in his faith\nthat: \u201cYou will find angling to be\nlike the virtue of humility, which\nhas a calmness of spirit and a world\nof other blessings attending upon it.\u201d\nMankind is essentially adventur\nous. That is why gambling in one\nform or another is the biggest busi\nness in the world\u2014with plenty of\nlosers every minute.\nThis and That\nBy Charles E. Jracevoell.\n\u201cHIGH STREET S E.\n\u201cDear Sir:\n\u201cI would like to ask you about a pet\nmockingbird that has lived in our garden\nwinter and summer for the last five or\nsix years.\n\u201cHe and his mate, who returns each\nspring, have raised several families in\nour rose arbor and other times in yards\naround us.\n\u201cWe call the male bird Scampy as he\nused to sit on the grape arbor and chase\nall the other birds away, even the\npigeons. He is very tame, and knows my\nvoice, and whenever I go out into the\ngarden he follows me around.\n\u201cWhen I had my dog and would take\nhim to the woods for a walk Scampy\nwould fly along with us, and actually\ntalk to us.\n\u201cBut I feel so sad\u2014about three weeks\nago he came to the back porch, and I\nnoticed one leg was hanging limp, and\nhe kept picking under his wing, as I\ncould not get near enough to him to\ncatch him and I did not want to frighten\nhim.\n\u201cHe seems to want me to do something\nfor him, though. He still comes for his\nraisins as I put them on a shelf so he\ndoes not have to stand too long on\none foot.\n\u201cHe can fly but has no use of that\nlimp leg as yet. His mate is very atten\ntive to him, but his \u2018fight\u2019 is all gone,\nand he looks so pitiful.\n\"Will he ever gain the use of that leg,\nand will he live through the cold w\u2019inter?\n\u201cCould I encourage him into a cage?\n\u201cHe will come onto the porch and\nright on the table looking for raisins,\nbut since I have put my screens up on\nthe porch he cannot get inside, but sits\non the arbor until I come out.\n\"Yours sincerely, M. A. H.\u2019\u2019\n\u201cL STREET.\n\u201cDear Sir:\n\"I have enjoyed your articles in The\nStar for years and have sent many of\nthem to my sisters in Chester County,\nPa. They are ardent bird lovers and\nhave recently moved to West Chester,\nthe county seat.\n\u201cIn a letter received yesterday, she\nsays: \u2018We enjoyed the clippings. Our\nmockingbird has us very much worried,\nas we have not seen or heard it for four\nor five days. The raisins put on the\nwindowsill are still there. It was spend\ning most of the time here, and if it has\ngone to meet its mate it surely would\ncome back to us.\u2019\n\u201cI wonder if you can give any explana\ntion of its sudden disappearance other\nthan that it may have met with an\naccident?\n\u201cYours very sincerely, E. W.\u201d\n\nMockingbirds are large, hearty fellows,\nand, like most hearty fellows, are likely\nto get into trouble.\nMany of them get crippled legs, and\nmost of these manage to get along very\nwell.\nNature finally \u201ccures,\u201d at least to some\nextent, the broken member, and the\nvictim learns to balance itself on its one\ngood leg and tail.\nMost species can stiffen the tail feath\ners at will.\nAn example of this may be seen in the\nlittle downy woodpecker, which often\nleans back on its tail as it hammers at\na tree.\nA crippled mocker usually lives through\nthe winters, provided that some human\nbeing sees to it that he has plenty of\nfood, including bread and raisins.\nAlmost any bird may be trapped, but\na wildbird often fights incarceration so\ndesperately that it is better off outdoors,\neven if crippled. Care must be taken to\nsee that such a bird is permitted to eat.\nThis means seeing to it that he has a\nspecial feeding place, and that other\nbirds are not permitted to visit it very\nmuch.\nMockingbirds often nest across the\nstreet, or up the block, rather than in\nthe place the male may have lived all\nwinter. In such cases it may be sev\neral weeks before they return to the old\nplace. Sometimes they may not come\nback until winter.\nf\nLetters to The Star\nReaders Discuss Famine Abroad\nFrom Different Angles\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nIt is my belief that in every one of\nus there is a desire to do something\ngreat, to be great. We all need to feel\nnow and then that something we have\ndone was worth while, that we have been\nlifted above our usual stature by a job\nwell done, or help given when urgently\nneeded.\nNow, today and for some time to come,\nthere is given to each of us an opportu\nnity not only to do something line; we\neach can save a life, save many lives.\nIf we were able to look individually into\nthe faces of starving people everywhere,\nwe would be very glad to share w'hat we\nhave in order that they might look for\nward to tomorrow and next year.\nIt actually is within the pow'er of\nevery one in this country to save life, to\ndo the great thing we all Want to do.\nIt is not a cross for us to bear, but a\nblessing w'e should thank God for, this\nopportunity to waste less, plan meals\nnuJre carefully, and by examp\u2019e en\ncourage others, that men, women and\nlittle children may live.\nIf we do this, we shall experience the\njoy that comes from having done a\ngreat thing; if we fail, God help us all.\nWe Americans have been blessed far\nbeyond our merit. Let us show our ap\npreciation by sharing what we have,\nthat we may look back with pride and\nnot with shame upon 1946 and 1947.\nIt is up to each of us, individually, to\naccept this responsibility.\nMRS. MARTHA A. POWELL.\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nEvery day we are told over the air\nwaves of the famine in Europe and Asia.\nWe are asked to eat less, to waste less\nand make every effort to save food for\nshipment to the needy.\nI have a small farm and I know that\nI am speaking for every small farmer\nfrom coast to coast when I say that we,\nor rather those wrho are most vocifer\nous over the program, are approaching\nIt from the wrong end.\nFor over a year now, I have been try\ning to buy a farm tractor and imple\nments. I visited every dealer in Wash\nington, Baltimore, Fredericksburg, Rich\nmond, all the way down to Charlotte,\nN. C. They all laughed at me when I\nasked them when I could buy the needed\ntools. Their buildings are practically\nempty.\nHow can we feed the hapless, famine\nstricken millions in addition to ourselves,\nwhen no efforts are made to provide the\nfarmers with the tools which they so\nbadly need to plant and to harvest the\nfoods which every one of us is as^ed\nover and over not to waste? Who gets\nall the tractors which manufacturers\u2019\nagents tell me have been and are being\nturned out regularly, although on a\nlimited scale? How do black marketeers\nget hold of them?\nAnswering an ad, I finally reached a\nspot in the woods not far from Wash\nington where a man who claimed to be\nrepresenting a client had no less than\nfive tractors for sale. I was sorely\ntempted to buy one, even though his\nprice was $400 above the ceiling retail\nprice. Some think that I should have\nbought one regardless of the price. What\nwould you have done? Last year half of\nmy land stayed idle while the crops on\nthe other half rotted in the field for\nlack of equipment. This is hardly the\nway to raise foodstuffs for the suffering\nworld. L. DE KOZAN.\nNewington, Va.\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nHere is another viewpoint on food:\nMessrs. Lehman's and La Guardia's\nhard-boiled demand that food be forc\nibly withheld from our people and\nshipped abroad arouses nothing but a\nfeeling of resentment in my neighbor\nhood. Americans are a generous people.\nThey are responding to the call by Pres\nident Truman and Mr. Hoover for a\nvoluntary sharing of their food. This\ncountry, as a matter of fact, is doing\nmore than its part.\nBut compulsion in the matter is\nanother thing. It at once strips away\nthe mask of generosity and shows up\na hard face of political interest.\nHearing Mr. Lehman talk in Wash\nington Tuesday night, one would think\nthat our blessed wheat, meat, milk and\nfats are something that America came\nby and utilizes dishonorably. These\ncharges of gluttony, made by New York\nmillionaires, will not impress the rank\nand file of our households. Have we\nnot pulled in our belts and given the\nworld free food these past five years on\na scale never before seen in history?\nWe had to do much the same during\nand after the other war.\nI hear of children in England who\nhave never tasted bananas, and I am\nsorry for them. But there are 5-year\nolcf children right here, related to me,\nwho never had tasted bananas or pine\napples until this month, who hardly\nknow the taste of butter or even mar\ngarine, have been forced all their young\nlives to eat more frankfurters than good\nmeat. To them cheese has been a rarity\nand a free sugar bowl is unknown. We\nhave gone a year at a time without\nchicken, a year virtually without pota\ntoes, two years without pork, this past\nyear virtually without apples or onions\nand almost w-ithout canned fruit. We all\nfeel like helping the hungry people\noverseas. But the war is over now. If\ncoercion is to be applied again. I for\none will meet it in whatever way is\nnecessary to give our own youngsters\nfirst call. A. B.\nCriticizes Lady Astor\u2019s Speech\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nOn April 8 Lady Astor, \u201cthe'\u2019 Lady\nAstor, honored the students at Dunbar\nHigh School with a visit and a talk.\nThe speech made good listening as lar\nas the brevity, the witticisms and the\nface value of the words went. How\never, it left a bad taste in my mouth\nand the discussions I heard later per\ntaining to the speech left an even worse\ntaste.\nThe \u201clady\u2019\u2019 used several stereotyped\nfigures of speech that are known to be\ndistasteful to us and which could have\nbeen substituted for words of a duller\npoint. Between the period of a sen\ntence and the capital of the next were\nimplications and things left unsaid\nthat have been construed to their ugliest\nforms.\nIt seems to me that a lady who has\nhad so much diplomatic experience, and\nwho has professed so many religious\nideals, would have known better how to\napproach a group of people and not\noffend them to the core, intentionally\nor otherwise.\n(MISS) JACQUELYN I. BRYANT.\n\nThis Changing World\nBy Constantine Brown\nOne of the most serious handicaps\non American foreign-policy framers is\nthe difficulty of obtaining reasonably\naccurate information about what is\ngoing on in areas which the Russians\nhold in a heavy shroud of secrecy.\nThe State, War and Navy Depart\nments know officially only what the\nRussians want us to know. Unofficial\nreports\u2014from agents of all kinds\u2014are\nnot always reliable. These men and\nwomen work under very difficult con\nditions. They are less in search of\nmilitary information than information\non actual conditions which prevail in\nthe areas under Russian occupation in\nGermany, the Balkans, Central Europe\nand the Middle East.\nThe decision of the Teheran govern\nment to muzzle the local press and for\neign reporters was prompted by orders\nfrom Moscow. The Soviets have never\nliked the prying activities of these men\nwho search for news, and have cur\ntailed their activities drastically by cen\nsorship and refusal to permit them to\nmove anywhere without government\n\"escorts.\u201d These escorts see that no\nbody but government-selected people\nare approached by the correspondents\nof newspapers in the western democ\nracies and allow them to travel only in\nareas \"open\u201d to them.\nWhile Russian correspondents have\nthe right to travel all over the United\nStates, Britain and other western demo\ncratic countries w'here constitutional\ngovernments exist, the reporters of these\ncountries are treated by the Soviet and\nits satellites as undesirable aliens W'ho\nshould be watched with utmost care.\n\nAmerican diplomats are, in fact, as\nmuch restricted as the unofficial Amer\nican observers\u2014the foreign correspond\nents. They receive permits to travel\nwith greater ease. But they, too, are\nfollowed by agents of the secret state\npolice which, while not bothering them\ndirectly, do shadow them. Any native,\nexcept those designated by the govern\nment, who dares to speak privately with\na foreigner is doomed. He will \"disap\npear\u201d from his home within 24 hours.\nIn some instances American official\nrepresentatives are physically assaulted.\nThere have been several instances in\nwhich \"unknown\u201d persons have taken\npot shots at American military or naval\nmen. These incidents are always passed\nin silence, lest the already strained re- 1\nlations with Moscow become worse.\nLast winter the American naval attache\nat Warsaw7, Marine Lt. Col. Andrew Wy- I\nlie, allegedly was drowned in the Vistula\nRiver while inspecting damage to a\nbridge before crossing it in his official\ncar, driven by a Polish chauffeur. His\nbody w'as never found. His death was\ndescribed as an accident, but if a thor\nough investigation was made the Amer\nican public here knew little about it.\n\nAmerican businessmen, who in the j\npast could make adequate surveys of\neconomic conditions in the countries\nin which they traveled, are equally\nhandicapped. If they are permitted to j\nvisit any of the countries over which j\nthe \u201ciron curtain has descended,\" they\nare in touch only with high government\nexecutives and can visit factories or\nlook at the economic conditions only to.\nthe extent that they receive permission.\nWhile the Soviet representatives are j\narmed with perfect intelligence reports\nfrom the many agents Russia has all\nover the world, the American delegates\nhave to guess at what is going on be\nhind that \u201ciron curtain\u201d of secrecy. We\ndon't know, for instance, where the Yu\ngoslav military forces are concentrated.\nWe don\u2019t know what is happening in\nthe Russian area in Germany. Ameri- i\ncans are not allowed to move even a\nfew miles east of Berlin.\nThe Russians are playing no favorites j\nFor instance, about three months ago\na reporter of the Communist Daily\nWorker W\u2019as urged to interview\u2019 the\nwidow\u2019 of the well-known Communist\nleader Theilman. who was killed short\nly before V-E day. Although his loyalty\nto the cause of the U. S. S. R. was with\nout doubt, he did not dare cross the di\nviding line and visit the widow, who re\nsided in the outer suburbs of the capi\ntal in the Russian zone.\nThe Political Mill\nBy Gould Lincoln\nNEW YORK, April 20.\u2014The issue of\ncommunism threatens to divide the\nworld into two camps. It is the under\nhung question which has caused much\nof the friction existing in the United\nNations since it first got down to busi\nness in London last January\u2014friction\nj which has continued throughout the\nj first month the organization\u2019s Security\nCouncil has been sitting in New York.\nRussia, which has emerged from the\nwar as one of the great powers, is the\nhead and forefront of the present\nideological drive to extend this political\ni philosophy throughout the world. Being\nrealists, the Russians have undertaken\nto extend their sphere of political in\nfluence into many countries as the most\nfeasible way of accomplishing their\nends. Although Russia and her inter\nests are threatened by none of the so\ncalled Western democracies, Moscow\ncontinues to scream from the housetops\nagainst the capitalistic nations. It is\nnot a hopeful situation.\nThe latest object of Russian attack is\nthe Franco Fascist government in Spain,\nwhose head the Soviet government de\nmands at the hands of the Security\nI Council. Its arguments for the over\nthrow of Franco's government have\nmuch to commend them to the other\nnations that fought against the Axis in\nthe recent war.\n\nFranco\u2019s government was established\nthrough the aid of Nazi Germany and\nFascist Italy. Franco did give all the\naid he could to the Axis powers, with\nout formally entering the war. Russia\nremembers with cause the Spanish\n\"Blue Division.\u201d which fought against\nher on the eastern front. Franco's gov\nI ernment is still Fascist, and Russia\ninsists that it has already become the\nI focal point for another Fascist effort to\ndominate the world.\nTire we j tern democracies have no love\nfor the Franco government. Indeed, the\nUnited States, Britain and France have\nbeen seeking for months in a diplomatic\nI way to put the skids under Franco. The\nUnited Nations Security Council, how\never, is faced with a principle\u2014the\nprinciple that there must be no inter\nference with the domestic affairs of any\ni nation. The one exception is that the\nI charter of the United Nations does\npermit of collective action when the\ndomestic affairs or situation in a nation\nthreaten international peace. And so\nthere is reluctance on the part of the\nwestern democracies to support collec\ntive action. They do not wish to estab\nlish a dangerous precedent\u2014particular\nly for the sake of the less strong coun\ntries\u2014of intervening to overthrow a\ngovernment.\nFurther\u2014and here is where the divi\nsion over communism enters the pic\nture\u2014the western democracies fear that\nif civil war is forced on Spain through\nthe action of the Security Council, a\nnew' field and a fertile one for com\nmunism will be sowm. In addition,\nBritain sees her life line to the Medi\nterranean and the East threatened if\na government wholly friendly to Russia,\nand perhaps unfriendly to herself, is\nset up in Spain. Already the Com\nmunist party in France is powerful,\nand other European countries are not\nanxious to see it extend into Spain.\n\nThe Russians argue plausibly that\nfascism got its start in Germany when\nthat country was militarily 'weak\nafter the World War. They contend\nthat simply because Spain today is in\nno position to start an aggressive war\nis no reason for not stamping out now\nthese cells of fascism.\nAndrei A. Gromyko, Soviet delegate in\nthe Security Council, had a real point\nwhen he said that noninterventionist\npolicies of the western nations\u2014par\nticularly Britain and France\u2014in the\nyears before Nazi Germany became\npowerful enough to seek world domina\ntion had resulted in catastrophe for all\nthe peace-loving nations. These non\ninterventionists, when Germany became\nstrong, were called the appeasers and\nappeasement was from the start a fool\nish policy.\nCommunism, to the democratic mind,\nis as much a totalitarian form of gov\nernment as fascism. It does not run\non all fours with personal freedom.\nThe fact that Soviet Russia, not content\nwith communism within her own bor\nders, never hesitates to proselyte in\nother lands is the principal disturbing\nfactor in the situation. That, and the\ncurtain which** Soviet Russia persistent\nly lowers over her own political aims,\nare what is hampering international\nrelations today.\nAll of this makes the task of the Se\ncurity Council particularly difficult. No S\none believes that Russia\" wants war\u2014\ncertainly not now. But what Russia\nwants is still the chief political conun-\ndrum of the world.\nOur Future Insurance\nBy George Fielding Eliot\nThe Army needs a force of 1,550,000\nI officers and men on Juiy 1, 1946, and a\nforce of 1,070,000 officers and men on\nJuly 1, 1947.\nAll responsible individuals have agreed\nthat these requirements are essential\nto fulfill our national commitments.\nThere is likewise general agreement\nthat these numbers cannot be assured\nby voluntary enlistment alone. There\nis some difference of opinion over the\nextent of the deficit if voluntary en\nlistment is the only means left to the\nI Army of getting its man-power require\nments. But that there will be a deficit\nl there is no doubt in the mind of any\ni one w'ho has really studied the problem.\nThe extent of the deficit depends on\nthe rate at which voluntary enlist\nments continue. If these go on about\nas they are now, there will be a deficit\nof 165,000 men on July 1. 1947\u2014about\n15 per cent below the required level.\nIf, however, selective service is discon\ntinued. and this fact has the effect\non voluntary enlistments which in\nj formed observers anticipate, the man\npower deficit on July 1, 1947, will be\nanywhere from 336.000 to 400,000 men\u2014\nthe latter being Gen. Hershey's esti\nmate. and Gen. Hershey is in a po\nsition to make a pretty good guess.\nThat means a deficit of 37!- per cent of\nj the Army's need: which are. it should\nhardly be necessary to add, the Nation s\nneeds.\nThe Military Affairs Committee of\nthe House of Representatives, faced\nwith these facts, tried to dodge its\nresponsibilities by reporting out a bill\nwhich is wholly useless to the Army\nand which in effect passes the buck to\nthe President to decide for or against\nrestoration of the draft after a five\nmonth enforced \u201choliday.\u201d\n\nFirst, it would permanently stop in\nduction of young men in the 18-19 year\nage brackets. Since these are almost the\nonly men now available, resumption of\nthe draft after five months would have\nlittle meaning. Only about 60,000 men\ncould be obtained. The man-power pool\nof the Nation is dry and the House bill\ncuts off the spring which feeds it!\nSecond, it would require the immedi\nate discharge of all inductees after 18\nmonths of service. The War Depart\nment hopes to reach this standard for\nj discharge of inductees gradually\u2014prob\nI ably in the fall of this year. To re\nquire its immediate application would\nproduce a definite shortage of 130,000\nmen on July 1, 1946.\nThird, the general effect of the House\nbill is a declaration by Congress that\nthere is no longer any necessity or obli\ngation to serve in the Armed Forces:\nThat we can settle back comfortably:\nJust relax. The effect of this, quite\naside from any other consideration, on\nvoluntary enlistments can only be imag\nined.\nThe House bill is clearly a gamble\nwith our national needs and commit\nments. The impression it produces on\nthe world will be that of an American\npeople whose representatives are un\nwilling to face up to their responsibili\nties.\n\nConsider, for example, the situation\nin Germany. There we have a consider\nable Army of occupation. That Army\ncan only be maintained at its fuil\nstrength\u2014the strength adequate to the\ndischarge of its responsibilities\u2014if it\nforms part of a United States Army\nwhich has adequate sources of man\npower for all needs. Otherwise there\nmust be compromises and adjustments\nbetween the needs of the Army of occu\npation and other responsibilities which\nthe Army as a whole must meet. If we\nreduce our occupation forces in Ger\nmany it is going to be very difficult for\nthe British government to convince\nParliament that the British Army of\noccupation should not be likewise re\nduced. The net result will be that the\nRussians, who labor under none of these\ndifficulties in the making of decisions,\nwill be more and more the preponderant\nforce of military occupation in Germany\nand will have, as a result, a more and\nmore preponderant voice in deciding\nthe future of Germany.\nWhat the nation needs, in this period\nof uncertainty and change, is insur\nance for the future. No one is proposing\na permanent extension of selective serv\nice. The Army\u2019s proposals have been\nperfectly objective and honest: The\nArmy has asked for a year\u2019s extension\nof the draft, to carry it beyond the\ndate of convening of the next Con\ngress and to assure the meeting of the\n1,070,000 requirement on July 1, 1947;\nthe Army has likewise promised that\nnobody will be drafted if sufficient vol\nunteers are forthcoming, that the term\nof service of inductees will be lowered\nto 18 months as soon as possible, that\nall fathers will be discharged at once,\nand that every effort will be made to\nuse 18-vear-old inductees on other than\noccupation duty. These are fair and\nreasonable proposals. The Senate, in\nits traditional role of national balance\nwheel, should support them and correct\n\u2019he timid flight from reality which the\nHouse bill represents.\n(Copyright, 1948.)\nUSSR Gold Transfers\nTo France Doubted\nProblem of Converting to Franc*\nWould Result in Detection\nBy Pertinax\nPARIS, April 20 (By Wireless).\u2014The\nreport, recently published in the United\nStates, that gold and foreign currencies\nwere freely flown out of Russia to the\nFrench Communist party has caused\nunusual interest here. In the past, the\nCommunists have often come under the\ncharge of being subsidized from Moscow\nbut the accusations brought against\nthem on that ground do not seem to\nj have been substantiated,\nj An official closely acquainted with this\ncountry's internal administration offered\nme the following enlightenment on this\nsubject:\nThe report published in America came\nfrom American sources which the\nFrench authorities feel they have suc\nceeded in ascertaining. But of the facts\nthemselves, French authorities have no\ndirect knowledge. They admit it would\nbe possible for Russian planes to unload\ngold and foreign currencies on French\ni territory unknown to any one here.\nOf two big airdromes in use today\non the outskirts of Paris, one\u2014at Orly\nj \u2014was rebuilt by the American Army\nand the French have little to do with it.\nAs to the other, at Le Bourget, it is\nunder French management but Ameri\ncan, British and Soviet planes landing\nj there are not held liable to be inspected\nby the customs and police officers,\ni Therefore, it cannot be rated a phy\nj sical impossibility that Soviet gold and\ncurrency should be landed in France.\nHowever, had gold and foreign cur\nrencies in any great quantities been\ndumped here, the beneficiaries would\nj n\u00b0t Acid it easy to have them exchanged\ninto French currency. Indeed, no deal\nof any sort involving gold and foreign\ncurrencies with which the Communist\nparty could be linked has ever been dis\nclosed to the police. And let it be well\nborne in mind that police spies, stool\npigeons and what is more, political ene\nmies of several varieties, keep close\nwatch on the Communists.\nCommunists Spend More.\nWith all the above a certainty, it is\nnot disputed that, from the day of lib\neration until now, the Communists\nhave had more money at hand than\nother political parties or groups with\nwhich they compete. Last October, the\nCommunists were believed to*have spent\nduring the election of the constitution\nmaking assembly now near the end of\nits labor no less than 4,000.000,000 francs,\none-fourth of that, sum being sunk in\nan elaborate network of posters and\nother advertising devices. By the same\ntoken, the expenditure of the Socialists\nhardly reached one-tenth of the sum\nput out by the Communists, while the\nradical Socialists of Edouard Herriot\ndid not have at their disposal for the\nelectoral campaign more than 8,000,000\nor 9,000,000 francs.\nMore than 60,000,000 francs, it is true,\nhad been paid out by the benefactors\nof the radical Socialist party but most\nof that money stuck in the pockets of\nintermediaries.\nWhere did the Communist funds come\nfrom? The common explanation is that,\nin resistance days, wagons of the Bank\nof France bringing bank notes to the\nbanks branches in the provinces were\nheld up and looted by Communist bands.\nThus the party chest was filled for\nmany months to come. Indeed, it is\nnot denied that, in the raids on the\nBank of France wagons, 2,500,000,000\nfrancs were seized in the district of\nPerigueux and 1.500,000.000 near Cler\nmont-Ferrand. But in the spring of\n1945, when the bank notes then in cir\nculation had to be replaced by bank\nnotes of a new pattern, no Communist\nmoney\u2014as such\u2014was located or iden\ntified.\nParty Members Pay I'p.\nOf course, it may be conjectured that\nprivate persons made it their business\nto help the Communists by bringing old\nbank notes, taken out of the party\nchest, and exchanging them as though\nthey were their own. At any rate,\nwhile so doing, they never were found\nout. The sums captured from the Bank\nof France convoys had probably been\nspent before the change in notes.\nNowadays, the ample financial re\nsources available to the Communists\nare probably accounted for by the fact\nthat the Communist party can muster\n1.000.000 registered members as against\n400,000 registered Socialists. On the\naverage, each one of them is disci\nj plined enough to part monthly with as\nj much as 100 francs in order to benefit\nthe party. This does not make as huge\nan amount as was in the possession\nof the Communist leaders last October.\nbut it doubtless points to a readiness for\nsacrifice on the part of the Commu\nnists unequaled by other political fac\nj tions. This readiness for sacrifice is to\nbe regarded as the mainspring of the\nsuccess achieved by the Communists\nlast year.\nNevertheless, within seven weeks now\nof the June elections, the odds are that,\nwhile the Communists will increase the\nnumber of their deputies in the govern\nment from 151 to some 180. the Com\nmunist-Socialist coalition, taken as a\nwhole, is more than likely to lose\nstrength, rather than gain.\n(North American Newspaper Alliance.)\n'Favorable Outlook'\nFrom the New York Journal of Commere*\nSeldom has the business outlook been\nso favorable as it is today. The great\nbacklog of unsatisfied demand assures\nindustry a market for all the goods it\ncan turn out. Consumers are amply\nprovided with purchasing power with\nwhich to pay for the goods they need.\nIt appears that a period of sustained\nprosperity is inevitable, and the stock\nmarket has been discounting just such\na development during the past few\nmonths.\nBut this highly favorable outlook does\nnot of itself guarantee that the nation\nI will enter immediately upon a period\nof prosperity. Unrealistic Government\ni controls and strikes can prevent an in\ndustry from functioning, regardless of\nhow large the demand for its products\nmay be. Shortages of some products\nprevent other industries from attaining\na high level of production.\nEaster Soloist\nGolden-haired and golden-voiced,\nReverently, she is raising\nHer rare gift of song, returning\nTo the Giver with her praising\nThis, her talent, multiplied\nMany times in power by choosing\nThus to magnify His glory\nIn the manner of its using,\nPurity of tone uplifting\nAll who hear her, clearly voicing\nSupplication and thanksgiving,\nDedication and rejoicing.\nHILDEGARDE WALLS JOHNSON.\nI","height":"32548","width":"23304"}}
